vibe: 2.0

meta:
  name: vibe_v2_vision
  description: >
    What VIBE is becoming and why. Defines the strategic pivot from
    runtime execution format to structured planning document medium.
  session_id: 2026-03-10-a7f3b2
  created_at: "2026-03-10"
  author: claude
  tags:
    - vision
    - strategy
    - v2
  status: draft

context:
  problem: |
    VIBE v1 was built as a runtime execution format: parse -> compile ->
    plan -> apply -> validate. But execution-focused AI SDLC tools (GSD,
    Cursor Composer, Windsurf, etc.) already do this well and will continue
    to improve. VIBE's actual differentiated value is as the structured
    medium AI generates planning documentation in -- replacing ad-hoc
    markdown with typed, composable, validatable YAML documents.

  constraints: |
    - Must preserve what works: YAML syntax, import system, artifacts, context
    - Must drop what doesn't differentiate: tools, workflow execution, retry logic
    - Must be usable by any AI tool (Claude, GPT, Gemini, etc.) via MCP or direct
    - Must not require a custom runtime to be useful

  assumptions: |
    - AI coding tools will converge on execution quality; planning quality is the bottleneck
    - Structured planning documents are more valuable than unstructured markdown
    - MCP is the right integration mechanism for AI tool interop
    - The .vibe format should be readable by humans and writable by AI

  scope: |
    This document covers the strategic vision only. Specific format changes,
    migration plans, and implementation details are in sibling plan files.

  glossary: |
    - VIBE v1: Current runtime execution format (parse/compile/plan/apply/validate)
    - VIBE v2: New document-oriented planning format
    - MCP: Model Context Protocol -- standard for AI tool integration
    - GSD: AI coding tool that handles execution well
    - ADR: Architecture Decision Record

sections:
  - id: identity
    type: analysis
    title: What VIBE Is
    content: |
      VIBE is the structured format AI systems use to produce planning
      documentation. It is to AI planning what OpenAPI is to REST APIs:
      a typed, composable, validatable specification format.

      A .vibe file is a YAML document that captures:
      - What problem is being solved (context)
      - What will be built or changed (artifacts)
      - How it was reasoned about (sections, decisions)
      - What "done" looks like (quality criteria)

      VIBE documents are the output of AI planning, not the input to
      AI execution. They are consumed by humans reviewing plans, by
      other AI agents continuing work, and by execution tools that
      need structured instructions.

  - id: anti_identity
    type: analysis
    title: What VIBE Is Not
    content: |
      VIBE is NOT:
      - A runtime or execution engine
      - A workflow orchestrator
      - A replacement for make/task/just
      - A prompt template format
      - A chat protocol

      VIBE v1 tried to be an execution format. This was a strategic
      mistake. Execution tools (GSD, Cursor, Windsurf, Aider) have
      strong execution engines with tool use, file I/O, and iterative
      refinement. Competing on execution is a losing proposition.

      VIBE v2 exits the execution game entirely and focuses on being
      the best possible format for the planning artifacts those
      execution tools consume.

  - id: value_proposition
    type: analysis
    title: Value Proposition
    content: |
      For AI systems:
      - Structured output target (better than freeform markdown)
      - Composable via imports (build on previous plans)
      - Self-describing (schema-validatable)
      - Session-aware (tracks planning across time)

      For humans:
      - Reviewable (clear sections, decisions, quality criteria)
      - Searchable (typed fields, not just prose)
      - Comparable (diff two .vibe plans structurally)
      - Trustable (quality criteria make "done" explicit)

      For execution tools:
      - Consumable (structured artifacts list with acceptance criteria)
      - Actionable (decisions already made, rationale included)
      - Bounded (scope and constraints are explicit)

  - id: execution_relationship
    type: design
    title: Relationship to Execution Tools
    content: |
      VIBE v2 does not execute anything. Instead, it produces documents
      that execution tools can consume:

      1. AI writes a .vibe plan (via MCP server or direct generation)
      2. Human reviews and approves the plan
      3. Execution tool (GSD, Claude Code, Cursor, etc.) reads the plan
      4. Execution tool implements the artifacts described in the plan

      The MCP server is the bridge: it provides tools for AI to write
      plans and resources for execution tools to read them.

      This is a clean separation of concerns:
      - VIBE: structured planning (what and why)
      - Execution tools: implementation (how)

decisions:
  - id: dec_pivot
    title: Pivot from runtime format to document format
    status: proposed
    context: |
      VIBE v1 defines tools, workflows, gates, retry policies, and
      execution semantics. This puts VIBE in direct competition with
      AI coding tools that have full runtime environments, tool use,
      and iterative execution loops.
    options:
      - name: stay_runtime
        description: Keep VIBE as a runtime execution format and compete on execution quality
      - name: pivot_document
        description: Drop execution semantics and focus on being the best planning document format
      - name: hybrid
        description: Keep optional execution fields but market as document format
    chosen: pivot_document
    rationale: |
      Execution tools will always have better runtimes than a YAML format
      can provide. VIBE's real usage has been in the planning documents it
      produces, not in the execution semantics nobody implements. A clean
      pivot avoids half-measures and lets VIBE own its niche.
    consequences:
      - Remove tools, workflow, validation top-level fields
      - Add sections, decisions, quality fields
      - Rewrite all spec documents
      - Build MCP server for AI integration
      - Existing v1 files are not forward-compatible

  - id: dec_mcp
    title: Use MCP as the primary integration mechanism
    status: proposed
    context: |
      VIBE documents need to be writable by AI systems and readable
      by both humans and execution tools. MCP provides a standard
      protocol for AI tool integration.
    options:
      - name: mcp_only
        description: Build an MCP server as the primary way AI interacts with VIBE
      - name: cli_tool
        description: Build a CLI tool that AI systems call via exec
      - name: language_plugin
        description: Build plugins for each AI coding tool separately
    chosen: mcp_only
    rationale: |
      MCP is becoming the standard for AI tool integration. A single
      MCP server works with any MCP-compatible client (Claude, Cursor,
      etc.) without per-tool plugins. CLI tools require exec access
      which not all AI environments provide.
    consequences:
      - Build Python MCP server with session management
      - Docker-contained for easy deployment
      - Spec and templates exposed as MCP resources
      - Planning prompt exposed as MCP prompt

quality:
  - id: q_vision_clear
    type: review
    description: Vision is clearly articulated and differentiated
    criteria: |
      - Identity and anti-identity are explicit
      - Value proposition addresses AI, human, and tool audiences
      - Relationship to execution tools is clearly defined
      - No residual execution semantics in the vision

  - id: q_decisions_complete
    type: review
    description: Key strategic decisions are documented with rationale
    criteria: |
      - Pivot decision includes alternatives considered
      - MCP decision includes alternatives considered
      - Consequences are realistic and actionable
